My opponent removes the Knight from danger.
I develop aggressively.
White interposes.
I offer to trade Queens.
White wants me to initiate the exchange.
I do so...
...and White completes the exchange. At this point, I should play ...B-R4 to prevent the Knight fork.
I overlook the fork, however...
...and White seizes the tactical opportunity.
Now at least White's Knight can't get back out via B7.
Oh well. I can win the Knight, so i'll only be down an Exchange. I'll fight on for a bit.
To clear a square for the B, so I can discover an attack on the Knight.
This B is en prise, but I'm too intent on winning the Knight to notice immediately.
I follow up with my plan. The Knight is trapped.
White guards his other Knight, presumably to castle without it falling to ...BxN.
I capture the loose B, and as White can do nothing to stop me from winning the Knight as well, White resigns rather than play out an endgame down 2 pieces for a Rook.
